name: 17alpha-ethynylestradiol
source: Hughes LD; Palmer DS; Nigsch F and Mitchell JBO. 2008 Why are some properties more difficult to predict than others? A study of QSPR models of solubility; melting point and LogP. J. Chem. Inf. Model. 2008. 48 (1). pp 220?235
Reason: 17alpha-ethynylestradiol is based on the molecular structure of estradiol, which has a melting point of approximately 178 C. The alterations due to functional groups are as follows: A cyclopentane fused to the D ring of the steroid nucleus typically lowers the melting point due to decreased symmetry and more flexible structure. The presence of an ethynyl group at the 17 alpha position introduces rigidness and some linearity that can increase the melting point, but its effect is less than that of a larger alkyl group. Additionally, the hydroxyl (OH) groups in the molecule contribute to intermolecular hydrogen bonding, which generally increases the melting point. In this case, the effects of the fused cyclopentane and the ethynyl group will both contribute to the final melting point. Let's estimate the effect of each: - Fused cyclopentane: approximately -20 C due to reduced symmetry and increased flexibility relative to benzene rings. - Ethynyl group: approximately +5 C due to increased rigidity, but less than a larger alkyl group would provide. - Hydroxyl groups: It's difficult to quantify the exact effect of the OH groups without more context, but we'll estimate approximately +10 C per OH group due to the formation of hydrogen bonds. Given estradiol's starting melting point of 178 C and the aforementioned adjustments, the predicted melting point would be approximately 173 C (178 C - 20 C + 5 C + 10 C (for the two OH groups)).
